text: That moment when you have demo in 15 mins and your app starts to bugg randomly
Guys, how many physical devices do you own to test your apps?
That's what you get with a small development team
<@U21R4GP5J> you should check Firebase Test Lab!
<@U0ESBF4AV> at the same time check your bank account
Yeah I have only one as well haha
Who don't generally care about it
Well I definitely don’t think we need 50, but at least 5 or 6.
They have server racks full of devices
It just goes to show how bad fragmentation is
otherwise firebase is really great. I am creating an app that is more or less using everything firebase has to offer
and i am enjoying what they offer
Backend as a service is still not really gonna cut it for big stuff
Right now im testing firebase error reporting. Not sure yet if it is better than crashlytics
Last time I tried (not my choice btw) Firebase on Android, its dependencies were huge
but i still need a third party server to do some operations that firebase cant do
I'm gonna use Prometheus in the future for event stuff
And perhaps if <http://sentry.io|sentry.io> implements Proguard, switch to that
Firebase test lab has a free tier
I'm switching to <http://sentry.io|sentry.io> for backend error reporting
Also Play console can do it too on a limited set of devices
<@U061HDV96> Maybe Google already planned this business model all along, fragmentation lead to need for automated testing :smirk:
If you're looking for a testing service
But I think it's worthed to use Firebase test rather than setting up everything by yourself
but again not meant for small business
Paying for devops can cost more
When was Fuschia coming again or whatever it was called?
And Golang, Rust... was gonna come with it?
iOS devs have it easy in this aspect
Huh? Why is this useless. How often do you run your Espresso Tests?
<@U04TK850N> well I expect you to have more than 15 tests if you're looking to test on multiple devices
What do you mean with “tests” here? Certainly not espresso tests?

>On the Spark and Flame plans, you can execute tests on 10 virtual devices and 5 physical devices per day (these quotas are refreshed at 12:00 AM Pacific Standard Time). On both plans, you can have up to four devices in each test matrix.
Espresso tests are only for UI...
This is your whole testset on up to 15 devices
What if you find a problem
<@U04TK850N> ah. Do they mean 15 tests per device then?
No, they mean 15 test runs. 10 on virtual, 5 on physical
You can run your whole testset 15 times
This is for spark and blaze
I’ve also been to the dev summit where they announced that :stuck_out_tongue:
It also states up to 4 devices per matrix
So you'd put all of your tests in 1 test?
<@U21R4GP5J|casadogg> uploaded a file: <https://androidchat.slack.com/files/casadogg/F3DEZ4UCE/captura_de_tela_2016-12-09___s_12.03.18.png|Captura de Tela 2016-12-09 às 12.03.18.png>
if you have 200 espresso tests, and you run them on one device it is still one test set ._.
Ok, but wer’re talking about test lab
<@U04TK850N> those will count as 200 espresso tests I think
Why would that count as 1 test?

> On the Spark and Flame plans, you can execute tests on 10 virtual devices and 5 physical devices per day (these quotas are refreshed at 12:00 AM Pacific Standard Time). On both plans, you can have up to four devices in each test matrix.
Are you sure that means all of your tests?
Because if it means what you’re saying it means, it’s not very clear.
Well it’s Google. Since when can they write concise product descriptions? :stuck_out_tongue:
Then I hope you can understand why we’re confused.
Test Lab was introduces after it was bought by google
